    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "```python\nfrom collections import deque\n\ndef shortest_path(graph, start, end):\n    # Create a queue with the start node\n    queue = deque([(start, [start])])\n\n    # Create a set to store visited nodes\n    visited = set()\n\n    while queue:\n        node, path = queue.popleft()\n        if node == end:\n            return path\n\n        # Add all neighbors to the queue\n        for neighbor in graph[node]:\n            if neighbor not in visited:\n                queue.append((neighbor, path + [neighbor]))\n                visited.add(neighbor)\n\n    # If there's no path, return None\n    return None\n\n# Example usage:\ngraph = {\n    'A': ['B', 'C'],\n    'B': ['A', 'D', 'E'],\n    'C': ['A', 'F'],\n    'D': ['B'],\n    'E': ['B', 'F'],\n    'F': ['C', 'E']\n}\n\nprint(shortest_path(graph, 'A', 'F'))\n```\nThis solution uses a queue to keep track of nodes to visit, and a set to keep track of visited nodes. This way, we avoid storing the entire graph in memory, which should",
